# NaaS 5G UPF HLD — Architecture Analysis, Uniqueness Assessment & Publishability

## 1. Executive Summary of the Architecture

Your HLD proposes a **4-layer hybrid eBPF/WebAssembly data plane** for 5G User Plane Functions, orchestrated by a Kubernetes Operator, enabling **Network-as-a-Service (NaaS) tenant plugin injection**:

| Layer | Component | Role |
|-------|-----------|------|
| L1 — Kernel | eBPF/XDP program | Fast-path GTP-U forwarding (~99% traffic). TEID lookup via `BPF_MAP_TYPE_HASH`. Exception packets redirected via `XDP_REDIRECT` to AF_XDP socket |
| L2 — User-space | Rust daemon + AF_XDP | Kernel-to-userspace zero-copy reception. Bounded payload copy into Wasm linear memory. Manages Wasm lifecycle |
| L3 — Sandbox | WebAssembly runtime | Executes tenant-supplied DPI/billing plugins. Returns verdicts: PASS, PASS_MOD, DROP, TAG, METER |
| L4 — Control | K8s Operator (Go) | Central Controller watches `WasmPlugin` CRDs. Per-pod Sidecar agent handles OCI pull + gRPC upgrade trigger |

**Core mechanism**: Hitless plugin upgrade via **RCU-protected atomic BPF map pointer swap** from plugin v1 → v2 with a drain window for in-flight packets.

---

## 2. Uniqueness Assessment (Prior Art Mapping)

I conducted 8 targeted web searches and cross-referenced your reading list. Here is where your work sits relative to the state of the art:

### 2.1 What IS Prior Art (Not Novel)

| Claim | Prior Art | Status |
|-------|-----------|--------|
| eBPF/XDP for 5G UPF fast-path | **eUPF** (edgecomllc/eupf), **Cable** (free5GC), **NgKore**, various academic prototypes | ⚠️ Well-established. Multiple open-source and commercial implementations |
| Wasm on Kubernetes | **SpinKube**, **KWasm**, **runwasi**, Envoy Wasm filters | ⚠️ Mature ecosystem. CNCF sandbox project (SpinKube) |
| Wasm managing eBPF (control plane) | **wasm-bpf** (eunomia.dev), Zheng et al. 2024 | ⚠️ Published and open-sourced |
| eBPF shared-memory processing | **SPRIGHT** (Qi et al., ACM SIGCOMM 2022/2024) | ⚠️ Top-tier venue publication |
| Wasm plugins for O-RAN | **WA-RAN** (HotNets '24, SIGCOMM workshop) | ⚠️ Published at a competitive venue |
| Atomic BPF program replacement | `bpf_link_update()`, **BPF Map Tracing** (Joe Burton, Google, LPC) | ⚠️ Known kernel mechanism |

### 2.2 What IS Genuinely Novel

> [!WARNING]
> **The Proxy-Wasm / Istio Elephant in the Room**: Istio's `WasmPlugin` CRD + Envoy's inline Wasm execution is structurally similar to Layers 3–4 of this design. Reviewers familiar with service mesh will immediately notice this. The genuine novelty is **not** "Wasm-on-K8s" (heavily prior-arted) — it is the **eBPF fast-path + GTP-U specificity + atomic BPF map swap for hitless upgrade**. The paper must explicitly differentiate from Proxy-Wasm by emphasizing: (a) kernel-level packet interception vs L7 proxy interception, (b) GTP-U header-transparent execution, (c) RCU-protected BPF map swap vs Envoy's listener drain.

| Claim | Nearest Prior Art | Gap Your Work Fills |
|-------|-------------------|---------------------|
| **Hitless BPF map pointer swap for Wasm plugin lifecycle** | BPF Map Tracing (Burton) handles stateful program migration; Envoy uses listener drain for Wasm filter updates | ✅ First to combine RCU-protected per-TEID map swap with Wasm runtime dual-instance drain cycle for 5G UPF. Sub-millisecond switchover vs Envoy's seconds-scale drain |
| **Telecom NaaS plugin ABI** (PASS/PASS_MOD/DROP/TAG/METER verdict API) | Envoy Wasm ABI exists for HTTP proxies; WA-RAN defines RAN-specific Wasm interfaces; Proxy-Wasm SDK is the closest analogue | ✅ No prior work defines a tenant-facing Wasm ABI for **in-band GTP-U L7 payload processing** with header-transparent execution. Proxy-Wasm operates on HTTP streams, not raw GTP-U encapsulated packets |
| **K8s CRD-driven operator for carrier-grade UPF plugin management** | Istio `WasmPlugin` CRD manages Envoy filters; NetEdit (Meta) orchestrates eBPF at fleet scale; SpinKube orchestrates Wasm apps | ✅ Novel synthesis — first to combine CRD-driven intent → OCI pull → Wasm injection → **BPF map update** on a live 5G data plane. Istio's CRD never touches kernel BPF maps |
| **Fail-open fault model for telecom Wasm execution** | No prior work defines fuel metering + watchdog timeout + AF_XDP backpressure as a combined fail-open strategy for carrier-grade sessions | ✅ Novel contribution to telecom reliability engineering |

### 2.3 Uniqueness Verdict

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The individual building blocks are established, but the specific combination — eBPF fast-path → AF_XDP zero-copy → Wasm sandbox → K8s Operator lifecycle — applied to live 5G GTP-U traffic with formal hitless upgrade guarantees, is genuinely novel.** No published paper or open-source project assembles these pieces in this specific way for the telecom domain.

The closest competitor is **WA-RAN** (HotNets '24), but it targets O-RAN RIC plugins, not UPF in-band payload processing, and lacks hitless upgrade guarantees.

---

## 3. Architectural Flaw Analysis

### 3.1 Critical Flaws

#### Flaw 1: AF_XDP UMEM → Wasm Memory Copy is a Throughput Bottleneck `[ACCEPTED — REFRAME AS STRENGTH]`
- **The problem**: Your design copies payload bytes from AF_XDP UMEM into Wasm linear memory on entry, and copies modified bytes back on PASS_MOD exit. For 1500B payloads, this is **two memcpy operations per exception-path packet**.
- **Impact**: At high exception-path ratios (>5%), this double-copy will dominate latency and limit throughput. Your "1% exception path" assumption is critical but unvalidated.
- **Decision**: Do **not** pursue shared-memory mapping (it destroys Wasm isolation). Instead, reframe the double-copy as the **measurable cost of tenant-safe plugin execution**. The paper should present this as a design trade-off contribution: safety vs. throughput, with the copy overhead bounded at `2 × payload_len` bytes per exception packet.

#### Flaw 2: veth Reinjection Adds Non-Trivial Latency `[ACCEPTED FOR MEASUREMENT]`
- **The problem**: After Wasm processing, the modified frame is written to the AF_XDP TX ring, submitted through the kernel, and re-enters the UPF namespace via a **veth pair**. Veth devices traverse the full kernel networking stack on the receiving end.
- **Impact**: Per-packet overhead of ~2–5μs from veth traversal (qdisc, netfilter, IP routing on the RX side).

**Reinjection alternatives evaluated:**

| Approach | Kernel Stack Traversal | Complexity | Verdict |
|----------|----------------------|------------|--------|
| **veth pair (current)** | ❌ Full: qdisc, netfilter, IP routing | Low | ✅ **Phase 1 choice** — works with unmodified Open5GS |
| **AF_XDP on both sides** | ✅ Zero bypass | 🔴 Very High — requires modifying Open5GS to read from AF_XDP | Future optimization |
| **tun/tap device** | ⚠️ Partial — bypasses L2/qdisc, still hits IP routing | Medium | Possible Phase 2 |
| **Unix domain socket** | ✅ Zero kernel network stack | 🔴 Requires UPF modification | Not pursued |

**Checksum interaction**: Because the veth path has no physical NIC hardware, `CHECKSUM_PARTIAL` (hardware offload) **cannot be used** for the reinjection leg. The Rust daemon must perform **software UDP checksum recalculation** over the modified payload before writing to the XSK TX ring. Cost: ~100–200ns for a 1500B payload — negligible vs. the ~2–5μs veth traversal.

- **Decision**: Proceed with veth for Phase 1. Measure latency. Use software checksum. Document "AF_XDP-to-AF_XDP bypass" as future optimization.

#### Flaw 3: Single-TEID Granularity for Exception Routing is Inflexible `[ACCEPTED AS OOS]`
- **The problem**: Exception routing is based solely on TEID lookup in a BPF hash map. This means you can only route **all packets** from a given session to the Wasm engine, not specific flows within a session.
- **Impact**: A session carrying mixed traffic (e.g., IoT telemetry + video) cannot selectively route only the telemetry to DPI while keeping video on the fast path.
- **Recommendation**: Consider adding a **secondary filter** (e.g., inner 5-tuple match after GTP-U decap) to the eBPF program. This adds complexity but dramatically improves flexibility.
- **Decision**: Keep single-TEID for Phase 1 simplicity, but document this secondary filter as a strong future work addition.

### 3.2 Moderate Concerns

#### Flaw 4: Drain Window Race Condition is Under-Specified
- Your HLD acknowledges that if a v1 invocation exceeds `drainWindowMs`, v1 is force-killed and "at most one packet per affected session" is lost. However:
  - What happens to the **Wasm linear memory** that v1 was writing to? Is it properly freed?
  - What if v1's fuel budget allows it to run for >100ms legitimately (a deep DPI scan on a jumbo payload)?
  - **Recommendation**: Define a formal relationship: `drainWindowMs > max(fuelBudget execution time at P99.9)`. Currently these are independent configuration parameters.

#### Flaw 5: Multi-Tenancy Isolation Model `[ACCEPTED — PER-SLICE WASM INSTANCE]`
- The HLD mentions `targetSelector: upfPodLabel: "tenant=enterprise-A"` but originally didn't define the isolation boundary.

**Resolved design — Per-Slice Wasm Instantiation:**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     UPF Pod                          │
│                                                      │
│  eBPF XDP Program                                    │
│  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
│  │  TEID Map (BPF_MAP_TYPE_HASH)                  │  │
│  │  Key: TEID  →  Value: {slice_id, plugin_id}    │  │
│  └────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┘  │
│               │ XDP_REDIRECT per slice_id            │
│       ┌───────┴───────┐                              │
│       ▼               ▼                              │
│  ┌─────────┐    ┌─────────┐                          │
│  │ AF_XDP  │    │ AF_XDP  │   (one socket per slice) │
│  │ Slice A │    │ Slice B │                          │
│  └────┬────┘    └────┬────┘                          │
│       ▼               ▼                              │
│  ┌─────────┐    ┌─────────┐                          │
│  │  Wasm   │    │  Wasm   │   (isolated linear       │
│  │ Runtime │    │ Runtime │    memory per slice)      │
│  └─────────┘    └─────────┘                          │
│                                                      │
│  Rust Daemon (manages all instances)                 │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Why this works:**
1. **Automatic isolation**: Each slice gets its own Wasm instance with independent linear memory. Cross-tenant data leakage is impossible at the Wasm level
2. **Maps to 5G natively**: Network slices are the natural 3GPP multi-tenancy boundary. TEIDs already belong to specific slices
3. **Free eBPF routing**: Extend BPF map value from `{plugin_id}` to `{slice_id, plugin_id}`. eBPF uses `slice_id` to redirect to the correct AF_XDP socket
4. **Hitless upgrade scoped per-slice**: Upgrade Slice A's plugin while Slice B is completely unaffected

- **Decision**: Phase 1 validates with a single slice (single TEID set). The per-slice isolation model is an **architectural guarantee documented in the HLD**, validated in Phase 2.

### 3.3 Minor Issues

| Issue | Impact | Fix |
|-------|--------|-----|
| No mention of PFCP integration for TEID discovery | Phase 1 uses static TEIDs, but the paper needs to address how TEIDs are dynamically learned from the SMF | Add a "Future Work" section covering PFCP session event subscription (Accepted) |
| UDP checksum recalculation after PASS_MOD | Required on the veth reinjection path since HW offload is unavailable on virtual devices | Software recalculation in Rust daemon before XSK TX ring write (~100-200ns). `CHECKSUM_PARTIAL` reserved for future AF_XDP-to-NIC direct egress path (Accepted) |
| Fuel budget sizing has no guidance | How does an operator choose the fuel budget? | Add a single line declaring `drainWindowMs > P99.9(fuel execution)` (Accepted) |
| No DPDK comparison | Reviewers at top venues will ask "why not DPDK?" | Move to the end along with WA-RAN in the novelty/related work section (Accepted) |

