## 4. Publishability Assessment

### 4.1 Target Venue Analysis

| Venue | Type | Fit | Difficulty | Recommendation |
|-------|------|-----|------------|----------------|
| **ACM SIGCOMM** | Top-tier conference | Good fit but requires strong experimental evaluation | 🔴 Very hard (~15% acceptance) | Aspirational. Need multi-node testbed + line-rate results |
| **USENIX NSDI** | Top-tier systems conference | Excellent fit for systems contributions | 🔴 Very hard (~18% acceptance) | Strong target if prototype demonstrates real-world throughput |
| **IEEE NFV-SDN** | Specialized conference | Perfect topical fit | 🟢 Moderate (~30-40% acceptance) | **Recommended first target**. Your novelty aligns precisely |
| **ACM CoNEXT** | Strong networking conference | Good fit | 🟡 Hard (~20% acceptance) | Good stretch target |
| **IEEE TNSM** (journal) | Transactions journal | Excellent fit for operator/management focus | 🟡 Moderate | **Best journal target**. Aligns with Kubernetes operator management focus |
| **Computer Networks** (Elsevier) | Broad networking journal | Good fit | 🟡 Moderate | Solid option |
| **IEEE Communications Magazine** | Industry magazine | Great for architecture papers | 🟢 Moderate | Good for visibility, less rigorous evaluation needed |

### 4.2 What Reviewers Will Require

To publish in a well-respected venue, you need to demonstrate:

1. **Working prototype** (not just design): Your Phase 1 scope is appropriate, but the code must actually work and produce numbers
2. **Quantitative evaluation**:
   - Fast-path throughput in Gbps (compare eBPF-only vs. eBPF+Wasm overhead)
   - Exception-path per-packet latency at P50/P99/P99.9
   - Hitless switchover time (ns/μs) during live traffic
   - Zero packet drop proof during BPF map swap
3. **Baseline comparison**: At minimum, compare against:
   - Open5GS UPF (vanilla, no eBPF)
   - eUPF (eBPF-only, no Wasm)
   - Your system (eBPF + Wasm + Operator)
4. **Scalability data**: Multiple concurrent TEIDs, multiple Wasm plugins, multiple upgrade cycles

### 4.3 Publishability Verdict

> [!TIP]
> **Yes, this idea is publishable in a well-respected venue**, provided you build the prototype and produce strong experimental numbers. The architecture is novel, well-motivated by real telecom pain (vendor lock-in + hitless upgrades), and sits at a genuine intersection that no existing paper has claimed.

**Strongest publishing angle**: The **hitless upgrade mechanism** (atomic BPF map swap + drain cycle) is the most defensible novelty. Frame the paper around this mechanism, with the NaaS plugin API and K8s Operator as supporting contributions.

**Realistic timeline to submission**: Based on your 12-week methodology, target **IEEE NFV-SDN** or **IEEE TNSM** as first submissions. These venues value practical systems contributions and the eBPF/Wasm/telecom intersection is directly within scope.

