## 7. Concrete Text for HLD Document Updates

The following are copy-paste-ready paragraphs to add to `NaaS_5G_UPF_HLD.docx`.

---

### 7.1 Add to Section 9 (Novelty and Prior Art Position) — Proxy-Wasm Differentiation

> *Istio's WasmPlugin CRD and Envoy's Proxy-Wasm ABI represent the closest architectural analogue in the service mesh domain. However, Proxy-Wasm operates at the L7 HTTP proxy layer in user-space, targeting request/response streams. This work operates at the L2/L3 XDP layer in kernel-space, targeting raw GTP-U encapsulated payloads. The upgrade mechanism differs fundamentally: Envoy performs a listener drain over seconds, while this work achieves sub-millisecond switchover via RCU-protected BPF map pointer swap. The two systems are complementary, not competing — Proxy-Wasm cannot inspect GTP-U tunneled traffic, and this work does not target HTTP.*

---

### 7.2 Add to Section 4.2 (Layer 2) — Checksum Recalculation

> *On PASS_MOD verdict, the Rust daemon recalculates the UDP checksum over the modified payload before writing the frame to the XSK TX ring. Software recalculation is required because the veth reinjection path uses a virtual device that does not support hardware checksum offload (CHECKSUM_PARTIAL). The cost is approximately 100–200ns for a 1500B payload, which is negligible relative to the veth traversal overhead.*

---

### 7.3 Add to Section 4.2 (Layer 2) — Metadata Stripping

> *Metadata header removed before writing to XSK TX ring. The frame written to the TX ring contains only the original Ethernet frame with any payload modifications applied.*

---

### 7.4 Add to Section 4.3 (Layer 3) — AOT Mode

> *The Wasm runtime operates in Ahead-of-Time (AOT) compiled mode. The 500μs execution timeout is calibrated against AOT-compiled Wasm, not interpreted execution. AOT compilation occurs during the warm-up phase (Step 2 of the hitless upgrade flow) and does not affect per-packet processing latency.*

---

### 7.5 Add to Section 4.2 (Layer 2) — Threading Model

> *The threading model of the Rust daemon is implementation-defined; multi-threaded dispatch with per-thread Wasm instances is the expected production configuration, following the pattern established by Envoy's per-worker-thread Wasm VM isolation. The Phase 1 prototype uses a single-threaded worker bound to a single AF_XDP RX queue to isolate variables for per-packet latency measurement and hitless switchover validation. Multi-queue scalability via RSS-mapped per-queue AF_XDP socket pools with shared UMEM is documented as future work.*

---

### 7.6 Add New Section — Multi-Tenant Isolation Model (Per-Slice Wasm Instantiation)

> *Multi-tenant isolation is achieved through per-slice Wasm instantiation. Each network slice is assigned a dedicated Wasm runtime instance with an independent linear memory region, ensuring that a tenant's plugin cannot address another tenant's packet data. The eBPF exception map encodes a slice identifier alongside the plugin identifier in the map value: Key = TEID, Value = {slice_id, plugin_id}. The XDP program uses slice_id to redirect exception-path packets to the correct per-slice AF_XDP socket. This maps the Wasm isolation boundary directly to the 3GPP network slice, which is the natural multi-tenancy unit in 5G. Hitless upgrades are scoped per-slice: upgrading Slice A's plugin has zero impact on Slice B's processing. Phase 1 validates with a single slice; multi-slice isolation is an architectural guarantee validated in Phase 2.*

---

### 7.7 Add to Section 5 (Hitless Plugin Upgrade Flow) — Drain/Fuel Constraint

> *Configuration constraint: drainWindowMs must exceed the P99.9 execution time of the fuelBudget for maximum-size GTP-U payloads. This ensures in-flight v1 invocations complete within the drain window. The default 100ms is calibrated assuming AOT-compiled DPI execution at P99.9 < 50μs, providing a 2000× safety margin.*

---

### 7.8 Add to Section 6 (End-to-End Packet Flow) — Zero-Copy Framing

> *The data path achieves kernel-to-userspace zero-copy via AF_XDP shared UMEM. A bounded payload copy (2 × payload_len bytes per exception-path packet) is performed at the Wasm boundary to preserve Wasm linear memory isolation. This is a deliberate safety/performance trade-off: the copy overhead is the measurable cost of guaranteeing that a tenant's plugin cannot corrupt the shared packet buffer or adjacent packets in the UMEM ring.*

---

### 7.9 Add to Section 9 (Novelty) — DPDK Comparison

> *This work uses eBPF/XDP rather than DPDK for three reasons: (1) eBPF programs run within the kernel and do not require dedicated CPU cores or exclusive NIC driver binding, preserving standard Kubernetes scheduling; (2) eBPF maps are accessible from both kernel and user-space, enabling the atomic pointer swap mechanism central to this work's hitless upgrade contribution; (3) eBPF integrates natively with the Linux networking stack, allowing the exception-path veth reinjection without custom driver development. DPDK would require a fully user-space UPF implementation and kernel bypass, which conflicts with the goal of augmenting existing 3GPP-compliant UPFs (e.g., Open5GS) without modification.*

